BRIEFLY 
Massachusetts drivers paid the highest auto insurance premiums in the nation in 
1987, an average of $655, according to a report by A. M. Best Co. The national 
average was $487, the Oldwick, N.J., company said in its annual survey of auto 
insurance prices. Iowa had the lowest rates, an average of $256 a year. 
Massachusetts rates jumped an average of $100 in 1987, an 18% increase over 
1986, the report found. After Massachusetts, the most expensive states to 
insure a car were New Jersey ($635), California ($623), Arizona ($602), Nevada 
($600), Maryland ($597) and Alaska ($588), the report found. 
